<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-06-16T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-06-16T02:00:00-05:00" n="487" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4468: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul in Charge at Canton</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Huston</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-06-16T15:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">June 16,
                                        1922—3 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received June 16—9:47
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Chen’s<note n="55" xml:id="d487fn55">Chen Chiung-ming; Governor of
                                Kwangtung, Commander in Chief of Kwangtung troops; and concurrent
                                Minister of War in the Canton Government.</note> troops seized
                            Canton 3 o’clock morning, declare constitutional government at end and
                            in favor of old Parliament. Sun’s body guards still fighting in
                            President’s palace. Sun supposed escaped Whampoa on gunboat.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Huston</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>